From: shollatz@beatles.d.umn.edu (scott hollatz)
Crossposted-To: biz.zeos.general
Subject: Re: Linux, Xfree with Diamond Viper (Long)
Date: 14 Oct 1993 13:23:24 -0500

In article <CEu96M.Cnu@spcuna.spc.edu>,
Chris Mauritz <mauritz_c@spcuna.spc.edu> wrote:
>Erik Nygren (nygren@athena.mit.edu) wrote:
>: --
>
>: I would like to post an unfortunate warning to those considering purchasing
>: computers from Zeos or any other company which includes Diamond video cards
>: with the intent of Linux or any of the other free versions of UN*X
>: OS's.
>
>In short, don't do it (buy a Diamond card for use with Xfree).
>

I had purchased a Zeos 486/33 in Spring 1992 with the intention of running
Unix System V Release 4 with X Window 11 Release 5.  My Zeos box worked fine
until I brought it in for a minor maintenance job (which was a virus on
my Unix boot drive!).  After I got my machine back I noticed that Zeos did
a free upgrade of the video BIOS.  I had a Diamond SpeedStar.  Now I have
a Diamond SpeedStar Plus.  This sort of screwed up my X386 timings.  To
compound matters a little more, the NEC 4fg monitor I used before the BIOS
switch had a small convergence problem so I traded it for a NEC 3fgx.
Bad move.  Timing problems again.  I finally got my video sync timings ok
after a year of fiddling.  I don't get *any* flicker under X at 1024x768
but I get it under MS-Windows at the same resolution.

Overall, I am satisfied with the Zeos machine.  Yes, it falls short of the
Sun SPARCstation I like to use, but it feels good to have a full-blown Unix
machine at home that I can afford.  But don't complain about Zeos.  Instead,
THE FULL BLAME SHOULD BE DIRECTED TOWARD DIAMOND.

-- scott hollatz



